Quote:  267 The basic principle was that joint ventures should fish stocks not already being taken by New Zealand fishermen, and not likely to be fished by them in the near future. The fishing of these stocks should require catching capacity and know-how beyond what was available in New Zealand.<i>Ibid.</i>

268 The 72-metre <i>Banshu Maru</i> No. 8 began fishing offshore waters in 1979 for a joint venture between Watties and the Japanese fishing company Taiyo, and operations like this provided some fish for local processing and built up New Zealand's offshore fish catch.
